{"meta":{"authors":[{"id":"6","fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:21 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:21 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">The verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> &ldquo;to need&rdquo; or &ldquo;to have to&rdquo; is used either as the main verb of a sentence or as the modal verb. It is also used as an auxiliary in the allocentric future constructions (xxlink 23.3.2 allocentric future).</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Like many other languages, Tibetan has certain defective modal verbs. This is the case with verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>, insofar as there are certain restrictions about how it can be combined with auxiliaries. As a main verb it means &ldquo;to need&rdquo; or &ldquo;to want.&rdquo; <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> occurs only with the following auxiliaries, and its various tenses (future, present, past) have to be deduced from the context.</p>\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཡོད་</span> &ldquo;I need&rdquo;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མེད་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> &ldquo;I want&rdquo;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative:</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་འདུག་</span> &ldquo;you, he need(s)&rdquo;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མི་འདུག་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་རེད་</span> &ldquo;you, he need(s)&rdquo;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མ་རེད་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">The suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span> may be inserted between the modal and the auxiliary: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་</span>, but it is usually dropped in conversation. As shown above, the verb may occur alone without auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་</span> and may then be best translated as &ldquo;I (do not) want,&rdquo; while with the auxiliary it may be translated as &ldquo;need.&rdquo; This negation is not pronounced <em>mi </em>as expected but rather is <em>mu</em>.</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">The subject of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་</span> used as a main verb must be in the dative and the object in the absolutive. In constructing a sentence, the beneficiary comes first and the patient second.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངར་ཁ་བཏགས་དགོས་ཡོད།</span> &ldquo;I need offering-scarves.&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངར་ཇ་མི་དགོས།</span> &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want any tea.&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་ལ་ཆབ་དགོས་གནང་གི་འདུག</span> &ldquo;He needs/wants water (H).&rdquo;</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">As a modal verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> means &ldquo;to have to,&rdquo; &ldquo;to need,&rdquo; or even &ldquo;must.&rdquo; In Tibetan, unlike European languages, modal verbs such <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆོག་</span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐུབ་</span> do not have an epistemic function and may not indicate probability or certainty (as in &ldquo;he may be there, he must be there, etc.&rdquo;). For the auxiliaries devoted to this function, see the discussion of epistemic mood here in the Reference Grammar (xxlink 11.3.1 epistemic); see also the discussions of the modal epistemic verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྲིད་</span> (xxlink 11.3.6 modal verbs).</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">The modal verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> goes with the following auxiliaries:</p>\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Future:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཀྱི་རེད་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Present:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Past   (perfective):</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་སོང་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་པ་རེད་</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Conjugations of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> are formed in the same way as predicative adjectives such as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགའ་པོ་</span> &ldquo;like/be fond of.&rdquo; The forms *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་སོང་</span>, *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བཞག</span> and *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་པ་རེད་</span> are usually not acceptable.</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">The case of the subject depends on the main verb.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱང་ཤེལ་བསྣམས་དགོས་རེད།</span> &ldquo;(We) have to take binoculars.&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཁ་བཏགས་ཉོ་དགོས་ཡོད།</span> &ldquo;I have to buy offering-scarves.&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངས་དངུལ་སྤྲད་དགོས་བྱུང་།</span> &ldquo;I had to pay (for it).&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་རི་ལིའི་ནང་ལ་ཕེབས་དགོས་བྱུང་སོང་།</span> &ldquo;He had to take the train.&rdquo;</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཡོད་</span> &ldquo;I need&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མེད་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span> &ldquo;I want&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative:</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་འདུག་</span> &ldquo;you, he need(s)&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མི་འདུག་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་རེད་</span> &ldquo;you, he need(s)&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མ་རེད་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Future:</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཀྱི་རེད་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Present:</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་</span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་</span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Past   (perfective):</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་སོང་</span></p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive</p>\n\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་པ་རེད་</span></p>\n","title":""}]}